                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/202</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-13T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 13, 1916, 6 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 14, 6.15 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4733. Referring to my 4724, December 12, 6 p. m. The Danish Minister called on me
                    to-day and in informal conversation intimated the same opinion expressed by the
                    Spanish Ambassador yesterday. He said, “If the Allies refuse the German peace
                    offer, we shall have to look out for our ships.” I find that this opinion
                    prevails more or less generally and that if the peace offer should fail, as is
                    generally expected, the Chancellor would be subjected to greater pressure than
                    ever before to reopen the ruthless submarine campaign.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
